# Dual Repository Git Workflow

This project maintains two Git remotes: Adobe (corporate) and Personal repositories.

## Git Remotes Configuration

```bash
adobe    https://github.com/AdobeManagedServices/OSCAL-Reports.git
personal https://github.com/keekar2022/OSCAL-Reports.git
```

## CRITICAL: Always Switch Git User Before Committing

### Rule: Check User BEFORE Every Commit/Push

**ALWAYS run these commands BEFORE creating ANY commit:**

```bash
# Check current Git user
git config user.name
git config user.email

# Check which remote you're about to push to
git remote -v
```

### Git User Configurations

#### For Adobe Repository (AdobeManagedServices)
```bash
git config user.name "Mukesh Kesharwani"
git config user.email "mukesh.kesharwani@adobe.com"
```

#### For Personal Repository (keekar2022)
```bash
git config user.name "keekar2022"
git config user.email "mukesh.kesharwani@gmail.com"
```

## Commit and Push Workflow

### ❌ WRONG - Don't Do This

```bash
# BAD: Committing without checking/setting user
git add .
git commit -m "feat: add feature"
git push adobe Development
git push personal Development
```

**Problem**: Commits to Adobe repo will have wrong author (personal email).

### ✅ CORRECT - Always Do This

```bash
# Step 1: Check/Set Git user for Adobe commits
git config user.name "Mukesh Kesharwani"
git config user.email "mukesh.kesharwani@adobe.com"

# Step 2: Verify the configuration
git config user.name    # Should show: Mukesh Kesharwani
git config user.email   # Should show: mukesh.kesharwani@adobe.com

# Step 3: Stage and commit
git add <files>
git commit -m "feat: descriptive commit message"

# Step 4: Push to both remotes
git push adobe Development
git push personal Development
```

## AI Agent Instructions

When asked to "commit" or "push" or "check in code to both repos":

1. **ALWAYS check current Git user first**:
   ```bash
   git config user.name && git config user.email
   ```

2. **If user is NOT set to Adobe credentials, SET IT**:
   ```bash
   git config user.name "Mukesh Kesharwani"
   git config user.email "mukesh.kesharwani@adobe.com"
   ```

3. **Verify the change**:
   ```bash
   git config user.name    # Verify: Mukesh Kesharwani
   git config user.email   # Verify: mukesh.kesharwani@adobe.com
   ```

4. **Then proceed with commit and push**:
   ```bash
   git add <files>
   git commit -m "commit message"
   git push adobe Development
   git push personal Development
   ```

## Quick Reference Commands

```bash
# Check current user
git config user.name && git config user.email

# Switch to Adobe user
git config user.name "Mukesh Kesharwani" && \
git config user.email "mukesh.kesharwani@adobe.com"

# Switch to Personal user (if needed)
git config user.name "keekar2022" && \
git config user.email "mukesh.kesharwani@gmail.com"

# Verify remotes
git remote -v

# Push to both repos
git push adobe Development && git push personal Development
```

## Why This Matters

- **Adobe repository**: Corporate commits must show proper corporate author
- **Audit trail**: Correct attribution for compliance and tracking
- **Professional**: Maintains proper separation between corporate and personal work
- **Git history**: Clean, accurate commit history with correct authors

## Branch Strategy

Both repositories follow the same branch workflow:
```
Development → Quality_Test → Pre_Prod → main
```

Always work on `Development` branch for new features.

## Common Mistakes to Avoid

1. ❌ Forgetting to check/set user before commit
2. ❌ Using personal email for Adobe repository commits
3. ❌ Pushing to only one repository (should push to both)
4. ❌ Creating commits with mixed/wrong author attribution

## Automation Note

The user configuration is **per-repository** (local config), NOT global. Each time you work on this project, verify the user is set correctly before committing.
